Calculate the average alpha diversity between these two sites. We are defining “average” as the arithmetic mean, or the sum of the species richness of each of the two sites, divided by the number of sites (in this case, two). If we represent the species richness in site 1 as \(S_1\) and site 2 as \(S_2\), then in the case of two sites, we can calculate the mean with \((S_1 + S_2) ÷ 2\). Remember that the sum of the species richness is not the count of how many species there are between the two sites. It’s the count of species in one site, plus the count of species in the other site---even if some species are shared. Input a numeric value; round to one digit. In some instances you may get a whole number, if so just include \(.0\).

The average species richness is 6 species. There are 6 species in site 1, and 6 in site 2, so the formula is \((6 + 6) ÷ 2 = 12 ÷ 2 = 6\).

Calculate the beta diversity of these two sites. Beta diversity is defined as: beta = gamma ÷ mean(alpha). Input a numeric value rounded to two digits.

The species present across both sites are:

a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, i

thus, the gamma diversity (\(\gamma\)) = 9, the total species present across the sites.

The mean alpha (\(\alpha\)) diversity is the average species richness = 5.5. There are 4 species in site 1, and 7 in site 2, so the formula is \((4 + 7) ÷ 2 = 11 ÷ 2 = 5.5\).

the beta (\(\beta\)) diversity is found via \(\beta = \gamma ÷ \text{mean}(\alpha)\). In this case, that's \(\beta = 9 ÷ 5.5 = 1.6363636\). Rounded to two (or fewer) digits, beta = 1.64

Which pair or pairs (set of two sites) has the highest beta diversity? Two or more sets of sites may share the highest beta diversity. In previous questions, you were calculating one shared (average) beta diversity across a set of sites. In this question, you should calculate beta diversity for each pair separately. That means you should calculate gamma diversity, and mean alpha diversity, only for each pair of sites, not for all of the sites together. You may or may not have to calculate every combination to get the right answer. To save time, you may be able to rule site pairs out that together have low gamma diversity and high species overlap. Remember that mathematically, we get high beta diversity when there is higher gamma diversity and lower mean alpha, which intuitively translates to high beta diversity when we have high total species richness across the two sites and few shared species between the two sites.
